# Next.js App Router Rules

## Routing & Structure
- ALWAYS use `app/` directory structure (App Router)
- NEVER use `pages/` directory
- Route groups: use `(groupName)` for organization without URL impact
- Dynamic routes: `[param]` for single, `[...param]` for catch-all
- Private folders: prefix with `_` to exclude from routing

## Server vs Client Components
- DEFAULT to Server Components — no `"use client"` unless needed
- ADD `"use client"` ONLY for: useState, useEffect, event handlers, browser APIs
- NEVER fetch data in Client Components — use Server Components + props
- ALWAYS pass serializable props from Server to Client Components

## Data Fetching
- ALWAYS fetch data in Server Components using async/await
- USE `cache()` for deduplicating requests across components
- USE `unstable_cache()` for persistent caching with revalidation
- ALWAYS use `revalidatePath()` or `revalidateTag()` after mutations

## Metadata
- ALWAYS export `metadata` or `generateMetadata` from page files
- ALWAYS include `title`, `description`, and `openGraph` fields

## Loading & Error States
- ALWAYS create `loading.tsx` for route segments with data fetching
- ALWAYS create `error.tsx` for route-level error boundaries
- USE `not-found.tsx` for 404 handling at route level

## Example — Correct Server Component
```typescript
// app/dashboard/page.tsx
import { auth } from '@clerk/nextjs/server'
import { redirect } from 'next/navigation'

export default async function DashboardPage() {
  const { userId } = await auth()
  if (!userId) redirect('/sign-in')

  const data = await fetchUserData(userId)
  return 
}
```
